  "reasoning": "1. Define the module interface exactly as specified in the prompt.\n2. Use localparam to define the two FSM states: STATE_LEFT and STATE_RIGHT.\n3. Declare a state register and a next-state signal as logic type.\n4. Implement sequential logic with asynchronous reset: sensitivity list includes posedge clk and posedge areset. On areset, state resets to STATE_LEFT. Otherwise, it updates to state_next on posedge clk.\n5. Implement combinational next-state logic using always @(*). If bump_left is high, next state is STATE_RIGHT. If bump_right is high, next state is STATE_LEFT. Otherwise, stay in current state. This correctly models direction switching.\n6. Implement Moore outputs: assign walk_left and walk_right based solely on the current state register.\n7. Ensure all constraints are met: all signals are logic, no inside/unique keywords, always @(*) for combinational, and explicit localparam usage.",
  "module": "module TopModule (\n    input logic clk,\n    input logic areset,\n    input logic bump_left,\n    input logic bump_right,\n    output logic walk_left,\n    output logic walk_right\n);\n\n    localparam STATE_LEFT = 1'b0;\n    localparam STATE_RIGHT = 1'b1;\n\n    logic state;\n    logic state_next;\n\n    // Sequential logic with asynchronous reset\n    always @(posedge clk or posedge areset) begin\n        if (areset)\n            state <= STATE_LEFT;\n        else\n            state <= state_next;\n    end\n\n    // Next state combinational logic\n    always @(*) begin\n        state_next = state;\n        if (bump_left)\n            state_next = STATE_RIGHT;\n        else if (bump_right)\n            state_next = STATE_LEFT;\n    end\n\n    // Moore output logic\n    assign walk_left = (state == STATE_LEFT);\n    assign walk_right = (state == STATE_RIGHT);\n\nendmodule"
}
